# Plan Ready? — Gate Review (re-check, post-research)

Reviewed: planner.out (plan.md, STATUS: READY) + pre-researcher.out (VERDICT: pass) for
trucking-freight-factoring-and-banking. Supersedes a prior gate-fail recorded in this same
file, which reviewed an earlier pre-research version of planner.out; that version no longer
exists, the research it was waiting on has since landed.

## Findings
1. pre-researcher.out resolves all 6 questions planner.out originally flagged, including
   both items previously marked CRITICAL:
   - Bridge mechanism: stdlib `urllib.request` reverse-proxy blueprint in mw-backend +
     additive `Start-Node` block in `run-server.ps1` (mirrors existing Start-Flask/
     Start-Tunnel pattern). Fallback specified if Node isn't on the Surface (external
     Node host, Flask proxies to its public URL).
   - Postgres for real-DB integration tests: local/Docker Postgres confirmed installed
     on dev machine for build-time tests; managed free-tier Postgres (Neon/Supabase) for
     live runtime via `DATABASE_URL`.
2. Reference monorepo structure, visual/design direction (accent locked to emerald/teal,
   no TBDs left), and factoring domain terminology/ledger formulas are all resolved in
   pre-researcher.out and folded into plan.md.
3. Required tech stack from the brief is explicitly addressed: NestJS, Drizzle, Postgres,
   TypeScript monorepo (Turborepo/pnpm via corepack), Next.js 15 App Router, RBAC, real
   (non-mocked) Postgres integration tests scoped to money paths, integer-cents currency
   discipline end-to-end.
4. Scope fenced appropriately for richness 10: 3 Nest modules, 4 tables, 6 routes, 1 hero
   + 2 supporting features, seeded demo accounts for login-based deploy-test.
5. Proposal-answer assets (Q1 cornerstone-construction + workflow-studio screenshot, Q2
   this demo, Q3 AI-assisted-dev take) carried forward correctly from brief.json.
6. Remaining open items are correctly scoped to later steps, not research gaps:
   - File-cap interpretation and the extra `run-server.ps1` touch need explicit CEO
     sign-off (CEO step's job).
   - Node-on-Surface install is an unverified physical-environment fact flagged for
     Michael to confirm before/at deploy, with a pre-specified no-architecture-change
     fallback — a deploy-time risk, not a plan gap.

## Conclusion
No unaddressed must-have requirements, no open research unknowns. Plan is well-researched
and build-ready.

## handoff
